situation. Drawing on extensive archival research, Prete argues that the British government's primary interest lay in the defence of the empire; the small expeditionary force sent to France was progressively enlarged because the French, especially Commander-in-Chief Joseph Joffre, dragged their British ally into a progressively greater involvement. Several crises in Anglo-French command relations derived from these competing strategic objectives. New information gleaned from French public and private archives - including private diaries - enlarge our understanding of key players in the allied relationship. Prete shows that suspicion and distrust on the part of both sides of the alliance continued to inform relations well after the circumstances creating them had changed. Strategy and Command clearly establishes the fundamental strategic differences between the allies at the start of the war, setting the stage for the next two volumes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zFrance. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zGreat Britain. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077357695740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773576957423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773576957/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles